It's that time again! Tune into this week's episode as @dogfishhead founders Sam and Mariah uncover the importance of land and water conservation at both Bristol Marsh Preserve and Cove Mountain Preserve. They also take a trip to Staten Island, NY to see how TNC is working to benefit communities impacted by Hurricane Sandy. 

As always, more on this epic roadtrip via our link in bio!

@dogfishhead co-founders Sam and Mariah Calagione embarked on an epic & eco-friendly road trip from Florida to Maine, learning all about TNC's conservation efforts along the way. 

In this episode, Sam and Mariah take a deep dive into the history behind Bear Island/Potomac Gorge in Maryland and the significance of our oyster aquaculture and restoration work amidst the pandemic. They also get a close-up look at how TNC is bringing nature's benefits to urban residents in Wilmington, Delaware. 

More on this road trip adventure and our work with @dogfishhead via our link in bio!

node.text:
Nature's health has always been a priority to @dogfishhead's founder and brewer, Sam Calagione. “Mother Nature, Let’s Do This!” (developed in tandem with TNC) follows Sam and his wife and co-founder Mariah as they embark on an epic and eco-friendly East Coast road trip from Florida to Maine. There, they hear more about TNC’s efforts to conserve our lands and waters, speak to local, environmental experts and explore Mother Nature’s splendors. 

In this episode, Sam and Mariah get their feet wet (literally!) with visits to our Blowing Rocks Preserve in @natureflorida, Goldbug Island Living Shoreline in South Carolina and the Black River Preserve in North Carolina. 

More on this road trip adventure and our work with @dogfishhead via our link in bio!

[Dogfish Head is a proud supporter of The Nature Conservancy (TNC) and its mission to conserve the lands & waters on which all life depends’ (www.nature.org). TNC does not endorse any specific product, including all those visible in the road trip docuseries. Purchase of Dogfish Head products will not result in a contribution to TNC. Learn more at www.dogfish.com/TNC.]

There’s a remarkable, intricate world of biodiversity just below the surface of the temporary ponds that form in our forests. Vernal pools fill up in spring as the winter snows melt. For a few months, they host breeding events for amphibians and macroinvertebrates.

A look inside the worlds of alien vernal pools from the latest issue of Nature Conservancy Magazine via our link in bio! 

Video by @stevendavidjohnsonphoto and @awilesmedia

People are influenced by what–and WHO they see. It's #BlackinNationalParks week–an opportunity to highlight those who are pushing for a racially diverse, equitable, and inclusive representation of the outdoors. 

"I've always felt that the national parks are places for everyone... that means me, that means you. As an African-American Park Ranger, I can show young people that they have greater choices than they ever imagined." Thank you, Shelton, for sharing your story!

"I was diving the break wall in Monterey Bay and this week in particular had over 40 foot vis for 3 days straight. I had been shooting kelp bursts all day as the light was exploding amongst the canopy above. I had framed this shot waiting for a sea lion to swim by. After 5 minutes, one swam up and paused for a few seconds, I took 3 photos and as rare as it was the moment left in a blink of an eye. The advice for anyone who's entering this year's contest: Get out there. Find a good story. Get the shot." –Tyler Schiffman, 2019 Photo Contest Grand Prize Winner. 

Check out our stories to see more of the opportunities that @tyschiff has had since the 2019 Photo Contest, and then be sure to swipe up at the end to enter... you never know what doors might open!

Have you ever considered that your favorite song has a climate change message hidden in it? 🎵

The talented multi-hyphenate @donaldglover AKA #ChildishGambino, has an easy breezy song called 
"Feels Like Summer." Don't let this song's chill vibe lull you into missing the meaning behind his environmentally driven lyrics: 

"Air that kills the bees that we depend on
Birds were made for singing
Waking up to no sound" 

Glover encourages us to slow down and question what's happening to increased summer temperatures and the animals that we have grown accustomed to. 

Check more incredible songs from artists like @billieeilish and @paulmccartney that highlight climate change, with the link in our bio! Do YOU have a favorite song with a climate change message? Let us know in the comments. 

📸: Guaravdeep Singh Bansal

node.text:
We are living through a make-or-break chapter in the story of life on Earth. In the last 50 years alone, vertebrate populations have declined by 68 percent. Today, a full third of freshwater and marine species face extinction, while countless invertebrates could disappear before we realize their full importance to their ecosystems.

Humanity occupies a unique position in this climax. Our actions this decade could either restore the ecological balance or tip it, causing species that rely upon one another within ecosystems to fall like dominoes—with devastating outcomes for human well-being. However overwhelming it sounds, there is good news hidden in these facts: We can still change how this story unfolds.

So how do we do it? Think of it this way: the sooner we start, the more we can save. TNC's Biodiversity Action Guide provides presents concrete examples of how nations can realize ambitious commitments and strategies for achieving a nature positive planet. And now you can download it via our link in bio. 💚

#biodiversity #takeaction #nature #peopleandnature 📸: @alernerphoto
